tion of Ca, Ba and Sr isotope fractionation with calcite precipitation rate. This behavior likely stems from the strong free energy of hydration of the Mg2+ ion compared to Ca2+, Ba2+ and Sr2+ which leads, during fast calcite growth, to the entrapment in calcite overgrowths of hydrated Mg ions whose isotopic composition is close to that of aqueous Mg2+. The strong dependence of Mg isotope fractionation on calcite growth rate suggests that, using the three isotopes method, Mg isotopic signatures of calcite in association with those of other divalent metals (Zn2+, Cu2+) have the potential to reveal mineral precipitation rates and thus environmental conditions of the oceans over geological time. {\textcopyright} 2013 Elsevier Ltd.},
